     @26 = ~Boots~
     @27 = ~The Paws of the Lythari~
     @28 = ~Boots are normally handmade by cobblers. Common boots are made by using a form, but good boots are designed for the foot of an individual.

STATISTICS:

Weight: 4~
     @29 = ~Elven Boots of Speed: The Paws of the Lythari
The origin of these boots is disputed, but one thing is clear: if they are of elven origin, they are either extremely ancient, or not from a subrace of elves common to Faerun. Rumors say they are not of the Teu-Tel'Quessir, Moon Elves or Silver Elves in the common tongue, the elves most prevalent in Faerun. Others say the remarkably lupine fur lining the boots is not that of a wolf, but rather a Lythari- elven lycanthropes so far from their elven roots as to be considered a separate race from elves by Faerunian scholars. These mysterious boots not only double the wearer's movement rate, but also provide free action. As with all items made (or aquired) by the Bladesinger's Guild and later given to their elites, so too are these boots warded for good-aligned elves.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Doubles movement rate
– Free Action

Weight: 2~
     @30 = ~Elven Chain Mail~
     @31 = ~Holy Elven Chain +6~
     @32 = ~The delicate yet sturdy craftsmanship of the elven races allows them to design many beautiful yet utilitarian goods. Among these is elven chain mail, which is so finely wrought that it can be worn under normal clothing without revealing its presence. This and its lightness allows it to be worn by Thieves and Fighter/Mages with few restrictions.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Open Locks: -5%
– Find Traps: -5%
– Pick Pockets: -20%
– Move Silently: -10%

Armor Class: 5 (3 vs. slashing, 7 vs. crushing)
Requires:
 5 Strength

Weight: 7~
     @33 = ~While in exile from Myth Drannor, Aslyferund learned the secret of fashioning powerful elven armor by gilding and heavily enchanting normal elven chain. Alas, his refusal to divulge the secret lead to his murder by a rival smith.
This particular suit has protected many elven heroes, and radiates an intense aura of goodness, preventing evil ownership. The link between <CHARNAME> and the Divine allowed this artifact of godly power to materialize in the Pocket Plane during the Time of Troubles; perhaps to advance <PRO_HISHER> righteous cause, or aid in <PRO_HISHER> defeat, should Bhaal's taint manifest itself.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Protection from Evil
– Immunity to normal weapons
– Open Locks: -5%
– Find Traps: -5%
– Pick Pockets: -20%
– Move Silently: -10%

Armor Class: -1 (-3 vs. slashing, 1 vs. crushing)
Requires:
 5 Strength

Weight: 15~
     @34 = ~Cloak~
     @35 = ~Bladesinger's Shroud~
     @36 = ~The cloak can be made in every possible shape with just about every type of fabric. The most common forms are a circular piece of fabric with a hole in the center for the head, and fabric draped from neck, connected by a chain, brooch, cord, or pins.

STATISTICS:

Weight: 3~
     @37 = ~This cloak sewn with blessed silver threading and enchanted for weeks while soaked in Elven Holy Water, given to Bladesingers who have valiantly defended the elven way of life, allows the wearer to avoid magical detection when a mission requires subtlety, and resist level drain when going toe-to-toe with powerful undead and denizens of the Negative Plane. This already powerful shroud has been further enchanted to allow the Bladesinger to use Improved Invisibility once per day, in truly dire situations when spells are depleted. It's obvious why the noble Bladesinger's Guild would keep this item from those with unlawful intent.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Immunity to level drain
– While hidden or invisible, the wearer is non-detectable by magical means such as Detect Invisibility and scrying

Charge abilities:
– Improved Invisibility once per day
  Duration: 3 rounds
  Area of Effect: The user

Weight: 3~
     @38 = ~Silver Ring~
     @39 = ~Bladesinger's Signet~
     @40 = ~A ring is a small band of precious metal that is used as jewelry. Some rare rings have had enchantments placed upon them that confer various magical abilities. These rings are highly sought after, especially by those of the adventuring profession. This ring is an unadorned silver band. However, its plain appearance belies the powerful magic within.

STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
     @41 = ~This ring is masterfully enchanted, granting immunity to silence while allowing the wearer to memorize more spells than normally possible and cast them more quickly. This ring designed by and for powerful elven fighter/mages is attuned specifically to good aligned elves. Bladesingers who have proven to be worthy protectors of the elven way are often given this signet to enhance their one-handed spell casting.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Can memorize one extra 1st-level spell, one extra 2nd-level spell, and one extra 3rd-level spell
– Decrease spellcasting time by 2
– Vocalize

Weight: 0~
     @42 = ~Long Sword~
     @43 = ~Seldarine's Fury +6~
     @44 = ~These swords are usually referred to as double-edged swords, war swords, or military swords. In many cases, the long sword has a single-edged blade. There is no single version of the long sword; the design and length vary from culture to culture and may vary within the same culture depending on the era. Among the most common characteristics of all long swords is their length, which ranges from thirty-five inches to forty-seven inches. In the latter case, the blade is known to take up forty inches of the total length. Most long swords have a double-edged blade and a sharp point at the tip. Despite the tip, the long sword is designed for slashing, not thrusting.

STATISTICS:

Damage: 1d8 (slashing)
Speed Factor: 5
Proficiency Type: Long Sword
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 4~
     @45 = ~Seldarine's Fury: Shame of the Gods
The creation of this artifact is unknown to all but the most legendary elves. Knowledge of the blade's existence is exceedingly rare; wielding it is unheard of. To grasp the beautiful golden hilt is painful to all but good natured elves, and deadly to enemies of the elven race. Those deemed worthy will feel the sword's sentience immediately as images of the Seldarine of Arvandor in a time before history flood the mind. Seared into the wielder's memory are vivid depictions of Corellon Larethian leading the elven pantheon in the creation of their greatest weapon, and deepest regret- for if this sword were to be twisted by evil, it would surely be apocalyptic. With the fear of the Gods coursing through your body, another feeling begins to manifest- protect the elven way at all costs. The wielder can feel the sentient blade bolstering their mind and reflexes, as well as their vitality being drained just from holding it. Clearly this wasn't meant for mortal hands.

STATISTICS:

